data.content:
Here's the full migration analysis and replacement code:

---

## API Inventory

| Removed API | Location | Pattern |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | `Stop()` | Blocking call interruption — wakes `WaitOne()` |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `Stop()` | Forced termination fallback |
| `ManualResetEvent.WaitOne()` | `RunLoop()` | Blocks thread, not cancellation-aware |

Both `Thread.Abort()` (throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`) and `Thread.Interrupt()` (obsolete `SYSLIB0046` in .NET 9) must go.

---

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly ManualResetEventSlim _newEvent = new();
    private readonly Queue<string> _queue = new();
    private readonly object _lock = new();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Thread? _thread;

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        var token = _cts.Token;

        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // WaitAny wakes on EITHER a new event OR cancellation —
            // replaces both Thread.Interrupt and Thread.Abort.
            WaitHandle.WaitAny([_newEvent.WaitHandle, token.WaitHandle]);

            if (token.IsCancellationRequested)
                break;

            _newEvent.Reset();

            // Drain all queued items (fixes original race where rapid
            // Enqueue calls could leave items stranded until next signal).
            List<string> batch;
            lock (_lock)
            {
                batch = new List<string>(_queue.Count);
                while (_queue.Count > 0)
                    batch.Add(_queue.Dequeue());
            }

            foreach (var item in batch)
            {
                if (token.IsCancellationRequested)
                    break;
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        lock (_lock) { _queue.Enqueue(item); }
        _newEvent.Set();
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();       // wakes WaitAny immediately — no Interrupt needed
        _thread?.Join(5000); // graceful wait; no Abort fallback needed
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts.Dispose();
        _newEvent.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* unchanged */ }
}
```

---

## What Changed and Why

| Original | Migrated | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `ManualResetEvent` | `ManualResetEventSlim` | Lighter weight; no kernel object until `WaitHandle` is accessed |
| `_newEvent.WaitOne()` | `WaitHandle.WaitAny([_newEvent.WaitHandle, token.WaitHandle])` | Wakes on cancellation **or** new work — no Interrupt needed |
| `while (true)` | `while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)` | Cooperative loop exit |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Cancel signals the `WaitHandle`, unblocking `WaitAny` |
| `Thread.Abort()` fallback | Removed | Not needed — cooperative cancellation guarantees the loop exits |
| Single `Dequeue` per wake | Drain loop | Fixes pre-existing race with rapid enqueues |
| No `IDisposable` | `IDisposable` | `CancellationTokenSource` and `ManualResetEventSlim` must be disposed |

---

## Key Pitfalls to Watch For

1. **`Thread.Abort` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** on .NET 6+ — it doesn't just "not work," it crashes at runtime.

2. **`WaitOne()` ignores cancellation tokens.** You *must* use `WaitHandle.WaitAny` with `token.WaitHandle` — simply adding a token parameter doesn't make `WaitOne` cancellation-aware.

3. **Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`.** Leaking it causes timer and callback leaks. Always wrap the owner in `IDisposable`.

4. **Cancellation isn't immediate.** If `Handle(item)` does long-running work, add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` checkpoints inside it. Cooperative cancellation only fires at checkpoints.

5. **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`.** If you add async paths later, let it propagate to the orchestration layer.

---

## Optional Further Modernization

For greenfield code, consider replacing the entire `ManualResetEvent` + `Queue` + `lock` pattern with `Channel<string>`:

```csharp
// Simplest modern equivalent — no manual synchronization needed
private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();

public async Task RunAsync(CancellationToken token)
{
    await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(token))
        Handle(item);
}

public void Enqueue(string item) => _channel.Writer.TryWrite(item);
public void Stop() => _channel.Writer.Complete();
```

This is optional — the `CancellationToken` migration above is the required fix.
